@ENDNODE

@NODE Button "RapaGUI Guide"
@{b}Overview@{ub}

    Button class derives from @{"Area class" LINK Area} and allows you to create buttons very
    easily. The XML tag's content is used as the button label. If the button
    label contains an underscore, RapaGUI will automatically set up the
    character following this underscore as a keyboard shortcut. If you don't
    want this behaviour, set @{"Area.NoAutoKey" LINK AreaNoAutoKey} to TRUE. See @{"Keyboard shortcuts" LINK Shortcuts} for
    details.

    Example:

        <button id="ok">OK</button>

    @{"Button.Hint                       " LINK ButtonHint} Set button hint
    @{"Button.Icon                       " LINK ButtonIcon} Show icon inside button
    @{"Button.IconPos                    " LINK ButtonIconPos} Define button icon position
    @{"Button.IconScale                  " LINK ButtonIconScale} Configure automatic image scaling
    @{"Button.IconType                   " LINK ButtonIconType} Set icon type to use
    @{"Button.Pressed                    " LINK ButtonPressed} Learn if a button is pressed
    @{"Button.Selected                   " LINK ButtonSelected} Toggle selection state
    @{"Button.Text                       " LINK ButtonText} Set/get button label
    @{"Button.Toggle                     " LINK ButtonToggle} Create toggle button
@ENDNODE

@NODE ButtonHint "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Button.Hint -- set button hint (V2.0)

   @{b}PLATFORMS@{ub}
        Android

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        When using buttons in dialogs on Android, you can specify a hint value
        that tells Android whether the button is the positive, negative, or
        neutral one. This hint value can be set using this attribute. You can
        set it to the following values:

        None      No hint. This is the default setting.

        Positive  Button is the positive button in a dialog (e.g. "Yes").

        Negative  Button is the negative button in a dialog (e.g. "No").

        Neutral   Button is the neutral button in a dialog (e.g. "Cancel").

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        String (see above for possible values)

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"I" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ButtonIcon "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Button.Icon -- set button image

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Set this attribute to the identifier of a Hollywood brush or icon to add
        an image to your button. Whether this attribute expects a Hollywood
        brush or icon, depends on what you specify in the @{"Button.IconType" LINK ButtonIconType}
        attribute. By default, Button.Icon expects a Hollywood brush. You can
        control the position of the icon in relation to the button's label by
        setting the @{"Button.IconPos" LINK ButtonIconPos} attribute.

        Note that RapaGUI might scale the image to fit to the current monitor's
        DPI setting. Please read the @{"chapter on high-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for more
        information. See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

        Please also read about RapaGUI's image cache to learn more about icon
        support in RapaGUI. See @{"Image cache" LINK ImageCache} for details.

        Note that on AmigaOS and compatibles icon support is only available with
        MUI 4.0 or better.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Number

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"I" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ButtonIconPos "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
