@NODE GroupIcon "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Group.Icon -- set group icon

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        If you define groups for a pageview, you can use this attribute to
        specify an image for this group that shall be displayed in the widget
        that is used to browse through the individual pages. See @{"Pageview class" LINK Pageview}
        for details. Whether this attribute expects a Hollywood brush or icon,
        depends on what you specify in the @{"Group.IconType" LINK GroupIconType} attribute. By default,
        Group.Icon expects a Hollywood brush. To remove the image from a group
        page, set this attribute to -1.

        Note that RapaGUI might scale the image to fit to the current monitor's
        DPI setting. Please read the @{"chapter on high-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for more
        information. See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

        Please also read about RapaGUI's image cache to learn more about icon
        support in RapaGUI. See @{"Image cache" LINK ImageCache} for details.

        Starting with RapaGUI 1.1 this attribute has an applicability of "ISG".
        Before that, its applicability was just "I". Note that on AmigaOS and
        compatibles changing the group icon at runtime for all pageview modes
        except list mode is only available on MUI 4.0 or higher.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Number

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"ISG" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GroupIconScale "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Group.IconScale -- configure automatic image scaling (V2.0)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        If @{"Group.Icon" LINK GroupIcon} has been set to a raster brush and RapaGUI is running on a
        high-DPI display, RapaGUI will automatically scale the brush's raster
        graphics to fit to the current monitor's DPI setting. If you don't want
        that, set this tag to FALSE.

        Alternatively, you can also globally disable automatic image scaling by
        setting the "ScaleGUI" tag to FALSE when calling "\@REQUIRE" on RapaGUI.
        See @{"Initializing RapaGUI" LINK RequireTags} for details.

        Please also read the chapter about high-DPI support in RapaGUI to learn
        more about supporting high-DPI displays. See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for
        details.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Boolean

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"I" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GroupIconType "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Group.IconType -- set icon type to use (V2.0)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This attribute allows you to set the type of the Hollywood image object
        passed in the @{"Group.Icon" LINK GroupIcon} attribute. By default, @{"Group.Icon" LINK GroupIcon} expects a
        Hollywood brush. By setting Group.IconType, however, you can make it
        use a different Hollywood image type.

        The following image types are currently available:

        Brush     Use a Hollywood brush. This is the default type. You can use
                  either raster or vector brushes. Vector brushes have the
                  advantage that they can be scaled to any resolution without
                  losses in quality. This is very useful when designing
                  applications that should be compatible with high-DPI monitors.
                  See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

        Icon      Use a Hollywood icon. This image type has the advantage that
                  it can contain several subimages of different sizes. This
                  makes it possible to provide images in different resolutions
                  which can be very useful when designing applications that
                  should be compatible with high-DPI monitors. See @{"High-DPI" LINK HiDPI}
                  @{"support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

        Note that you can globally change the default of all "IconType"
        attributes to Hollywood icons by setting the @{"Application.UseIcons" LINK ApplicationUseIcons} tag.
        See @{"Application.UseIcons" LINK ApplicationUseIcons} for details.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        String (see above for possible values)

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"I" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GroupInitChange "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Group.InitChange -- prepare group for addition or removal of children

   @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        moai.DoMethod(id, "InitChange")

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Prepare a group for addition or removal of children. Whenever you call
        methods like @{"Group.Append" LINK GroupAppend}, @{"Group.Prepend" LINK GroupPrepend}, @{"Group.Insert" LINK GroupInsert} or @{"Group.Remove" LINK GroupRemove}
        you first have to call this method to put the group into a special
        exchange state which allows the addition and removal of children. When
        you're finished, use @{"Group.ExitChange" LINK GroupExitChange} to relayout the group.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        id        id of the group object

   @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        see @{"moai.CreateObject()" LINK moaiCreateObject}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GroupInsert "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Group.Insert -- insert detached object after specified child

   @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        moai.DoMethod(id, "Insert", obj, pred)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This method can be used to insert the detached object specified by "obj"
        to the group object specified by "id". The detached object will be added
        after the child specified by "pred". After this method returns the
        specified object will change its state from detached to attached. That
        is why you must no longer use functions that expect a detached object
        with this object now.

        Before you can call this method, you have to put the group into a
        special state that allows the addition and removal of children. This can
        be done by running the @{"Group.InitChange" LINK GroupInitChange} and @{"Group.ExitChange" LINK GroupExitChange} methods on
        the respective group object.

        Detached MOAI objects can be created either by calling the
        @{"moai.CreateObject()" LINK moaiCreateObject} function or by explicitly detaching them from their
        parent by using the @{"Group.Remove" LINK GroupRemove} method.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        id        id of the group object
        obj       id of the object to insert
        pred      the object will be inserted after this object

   @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
