@NODE Listviewcolumn "RapaGUI Guide"
@{b}Overview@{ub}

    Listviewcolumn class is needed when creating listviews. It allows you to
    specify different attributes for the columns of your listviews.

    Listviewcolumn class must always be embedded inside a <listview>
    declaration. Its XML tag is <column>. See @{"Listview class" LINK Listview} for details.

    Note that you cannot create instances of this class using
    @{"moai.CreateObject()" LINK moaiCreateObject}. Listview column numbers are currently static, i.e. you
    cannot add or remove columns at runtime.

    @{"Listviewcolumn.Align              " LINK ListviewcolumnAlign} Set/get column alignment
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Checkbox           " LINK ListviewcolumnCheckbox} Put column in checkbox mode
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Editable           " LINK ListviewcolumnEditable} Allow editing of column items
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Hide               " LINK ListviewcolumnHide} Show/hide listview columns
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Icon               " LINK ListviewcolumnIcon} Enable icons for this column
    @{"Listviewcolumn.IconScale          " LINK ListviewcolumnIconScale} Configure automatic image scaling
    @{"Listviewcolumn.IconType           " LINK ListviewcolumnIconType} Set icon type to use
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Sortable           " LINK ListviewcolumnSortable} Make column sortable
    @{"Listviewcolumn.SortOrder          " LINK ListviewcolumnSortOrder} Set/get column sort order
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Title              " LINK ListviewcolumnTitle} Set/get column title
    @{"Listviewcolumn.Width              " LINK ListviewcolumnWidth} Set/get column width
@ENDNODE

@NODE ListviewcolumnAlign "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Listviewcolumn.Align -- set/get column alignment

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Set or get the column alignment. This can be one of the following
        values:

        Left      Left alignment. This is the default.

        Right     Right alignment.

        Center    Centered alignment.

        On non-AmigaOS systems this attribute is only supported for the dataview
        backend. When creating a listview and Listviewcolumn.Align is set to a
        value other than "Left", RapaGUI will automatically switch to the
        dataview backend. If you don't specify this attribute at creation time
        but want to set it later using @{"moai.Set()" LINK moaiSet}, you have to explicitly
        request a dataview widget by setting the @{"Listview.ForceMode" LINK ListviewForceMode} attribute.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        String (see above for possible values)

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"ISG" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ListviewcolumnCheckbox "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Listviewcolumn.Checkbox -- put column in checkbox mode

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Set this to TRUE to mark this column as a checkbox column. Checkbox
        columns show checkboxes instead of text. Whenever an item's text in a
        checkbox column is set to "On", "True", or "1", the checkbox will be
        selected. All other item texts will lead to an unselected checkbox.

        You can modify the states of the checkboxes either by using the
        @{"Listview.Rename" LINK ListviewRename} method or by using the dedicated @{"Listview.SetState" LINK ListviewSetState}
        method. Similarly, getting the state of a checkbox is possible via the
        @{"Listview.GetEntry" LINK ListviewGetEntry} or @{"Listview.GetState" LINK ListviewGetState} methods.

        To get notified whenever the user toggles a checkbox state, you have to
        listen to the @{"Listview.ValueChange" LINK ListviewValueChange} attribute.

        Also note that Listviewcolumn.Checkbox and @{"Listviewcolumn.Editable" LINK ListviewcolumnEditable} and
        @{"Listviewcolumn.Icon" LINK ListviewcolumnIcon} are mutually exclusive. You cannot create checkbox
        columns that are editable or show icons.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Boolean

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"IG" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ListviewcolumnEditable "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Listviewcolumn.Editable -- allow editing of column items

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Set this to TRUE to allow user editing of the items in this column. The
        user will then be able to edit all items in this column by executing a
        slow double click, i.e. slowly pressing left mouse button two times in a
        row.

        If you would only like to allow editing of some items in the column, you
        need to set this attribute to TRUE and you need to listen to the
        @{"Listview.StartEditing" LINK ListviewStartEditing} attribute. @{"Listview.StartEditing" LINK ListviewStartEditing} will then be
        triggered whenever the user attempts to edit an item and your callback
        can return FALSE to forbid editing of certain items. See
        @{"Listview.StartEditing" LINK ListviewStartEditing} for details.

        To get notified whenever the value of a listview item changes because
        the user has edited it, you have to listen to the @{"Listview.ValueChange" LINK ListviewValueChange}
        attribute.

        To manually start editing of a listview item, call the @{"Listview.Edit" LINK ListviewEdit}
        method.

        Also, @{"Listviewcolumn.Checkbox" LINK ListviewcolumnCheckbox} and Listviewcolumn.Editable are mutually
        exclusive. You cannot create editable checkbox columns.

        Note that on AmigaOS and compatibles this feature is only available on
        MUI 4.0 or higher.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Boolean

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"IG" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ListviewcolumnHide "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Listviewcolumn.Hide -- show/hide listview column

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This attribute allows you to show or hide single listview columns. Note
        that the columns will still be there, they'll just be invisible. Thus,
        you must not forget hidden columns when changing listview entries using
        @{"Listview.Insert" LINK ListviewInsert} or similar methods.

        On non-AmigaOS systems this attribute is only supported for the dataview
        backend. When creating a listview and Listviewcolumn.Hide is set to
        TRUE, RapaGUI will automatically switch to the dataview backend. If you
        don't specify this attribute at creation time but want to set it later
        using @{"moai.Set()" LINK moaiSet}, you have to explicitly request a dataview widget by
        setting the @{"Listview.ForceMode" LINK ListviewForceMode} attribute.

   @{b}TYPE@{ub}
        Boolean

   @{b}APPLICABILITY@{ub}
        @{"ISG" LINK Applicability}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ListviewcolumnIcon "RapaGUI Guide"

   @{b}NAME@{ub}
        Listviewcolumn.Icon -- enable icons for this column

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Set this to TRUE if listview entries in this column use icons. In that
        case, you have to pass Hollywood brushes/icons to use as icons to the
        @{"Listview.Insert" LINK ListviewInsert} method.

        Note that RapaGUI might scale the image to fit to the current monitor's
        DPI setting. Please read the @{"chapter on high-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for more
        information. See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

        Please also read about RapaGUI's image cache to learn more about icon
        support in RapaGUI. See @{"Image cache" LINK ImageCache} for details.

