@NODE Rectangle "RapaGUI Guide"
@{b}Overview@{ub}

    Rectangle class derives from @{"Area class" LINK Area} and creates empty objects that are
    freely resizable. This might not seem very useful at first but in fact,
    rectangle objects are needed very often to fine-tune the GUI layout. They
    can be used for all kinds of layout magic, e.g. for controlling the
    alignment of fixed-size widgets and much more.

    Additionally, rectangle objects are often necessary as padding space next to
    objects which are not resizable themselves. The <radio> object, for
    instance, is not resizable. To prevent these static radio objects from
    blocking the resizing feature of your whole GUI, you can simply pad them
    with <rectangle> objects. Here is an example of a radio object, padded using
    an invisible rectangle:

        <hgroup>
          <rectangle/>
          <radio id="printer">
            <item>HP Deskjet</item>
            <item>NEC P6</item>
            <item>Okimate 20</item>
          </radio>
           <rectangle/>
        </hgroup>

    By using rectangles on both sides of the radio box object, the radio box
    will automatically be centered inside the available GUI space. If you used
    only one rectangle object before the radio object, the radio object would
    automatically be right aligned. A rectangle object after the radio object
    would lead to left alignment of the radio object.

    If you need fixed size padding objects, use @{"HSpace class" LINK HSpace} or @{"VSpace class" LINK VSpace}.
    See @{"HSpace class" LINK HSpace} for details. See @{"VSpace class" LINK VSpace} for details.

    Rectangle class doesn't define any attributes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Scrollbar "RapaGUI Guide"
@{b}Overview@{ub}

    Scrollbar class derives from @{"Area class" LINK Area} and creates a widget that represents
    a horizontal or vertical scrollbar. An isolated scrollbar object doesn't
    make much sense. That's why scrollbar objects are typically connected to
    another widget by using the @{"Scrollbar.Target" LINK ScrollbarTarget} attribute. For example, you can
    connect scrollbars to an object of @{"Hollywood class" LINK Hollywood} to create a custom widget
    which draws user-defined graphics depending on the current scrollbar
    position.

    @{"Scrollbar.AutoScale                    " LINK ScrollbarAutoScale} Enable/disable auto scaling
    @{"Scrollbar.Horiz                        " LINK ScrollbarHoriz} Set scrollbar object direction
    @{"Scrollbar.Level                        " LINK ScrollbarLevel} Set/get current scrollbar position
    @{"Scrollbar.Range                        " LINK ScrollbarRange} Set/get scrollbar range
    @{"Scrollbar.StepSize                     " LINK ScrollbarStepSize} Set/get scrollbar step size
    @{"Scrollbar.Target                       " LINK ScrollbarTarget} Set target widget for scrollbar
    @{"Scrollbar.UseWinBorder                 " LINK ScrollbarUseWinBorder} Put scrollbar object into window border
    @{"Scrollbar.Visible                      " LINK ScrollbarVisible} Set/get number of visible entries
@ENDNODE

