@NODE Scrollcanvas "RapaGUI Guide"
@{b}Overview@{ub}

    Scrollcanvas class derives from @{"Area class" LINK Area} and creates a canvas with
    scrollbars attached. You can draw custom graphics to this canvas via a paint
    callback that is automatically invoked whenever content needs to be drawn.
    You just need to set up a notification on the @{"Scrollcanvas.Paint" LINK ScrollcanvasPaint} attribute
    and your event handler will be called whenever content needs to be drawn.
    The same thing can be achieved by embedding a widget derived from @{"Hollywood" LINK Hollywood}
    @{"class" LINK Hollywood} inside a scrollgroup or connecting such a Hollywood widget to
    scrollbars but Scrollcanvas class is preferable in some cases because it is
    optimized especially for scrolled content, i.e. it tries to minimize
    painting by using OS widgets which are specifically designed for displaying
    scrolled content. Thus, it is usually faster than the two solutions outlined
    above.

    You can set the canvas dimensions by using the @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtWidth" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtWidth} and
    @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtHeight" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtHeight}. Since Scrollcanvas class uses scrollbars, the
    dimensions of the canvas can obviously be much bigger than the physical
    dimensions of the scrollcanvas widget. As with all other classes, you can
    set those physical dimensions using the generic @{"Area.Width" LINK AreaWidth} and @{"Area.Height" LINK AreaHeight}
    attributes.

    To force a complete redraw of your widget, just run the @{"Area.Redraw" LINK AreaRedraw} method
    on your object. Running @{"Area.Redraw" LINK AreaRedraw} on your object will result in your paint
    function being called so that you can update the canvas accordingly.

    With Scrollcanvas class the dimensions you specify in @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtWidth" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtWidth}
    and @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtHeight" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtHeight} are in @{"device-independent pixels" LINK DIP} by default and
    RapaGUI will automatically apply the system's scale factor to the contents
    drawn by the @{"Scrollcanvas.Paint" LINK ScrollcanvasPaint} function. If you want to have fine-tuned
    control, you can set the @{"Scrollcanvas.AutoScale" LINK ScrollcanvasAutoScale} attribute to FALSE. In that
    case, @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtWidth" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtWidth} and @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtHeight" LINK ScrollcanvasVirtHeight} are interpreted as
    physical pixels and no auto scaling will be done so that your paint function
    can draw high resolutions graphics without any quality loss due to scaling.
    See @{"High-DPI support" LINK HiDPI} for details.

    @{"Scrollcanvas.AutoBars              " LINK ScrollcanvasAutoBars} Set scrollbar visibility
    @{"Scrollcanvas.AutoScale             " LINK ScrollcanvasAutoScale} Enable/disable autoscaling
    @{"Scrollcanvas.Paint                 " LINK ScrollcanvasPaint} Request paint notification
    @{"Scrollcanvas.Scroll                " LINK ScrollcanvasScroll} Scroll the canvas
    @{"Scrollcanvas.ScrollX               " LINK ScrollcanvasScrollX} Get horizontal scroll position
    @{"Scrollcanvas.ScrollY               " LINK ScrollcanvasScrollY} Get vertical scroll position
    @{"Scrollcanvas.StepSize              " LINK ScrollcanvasStepSize} Set/get scrollbar step size
    @{"Scrollcanvas.UseLeftBorder         " LINK ScrollcanvasUseLeftBorder} Use left border scroller
    @{"Scrollcanvas.UseWinBorder          " LINK ScrollcanvasUseWinBorder} Use window scrollbars for this scrollcanvas
    @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtHeight            " LINK ScrollcanvasVirtHeight} Set/get canvas height
    @{"Scrollcanvas.VirtWidth             " LINK ScrollcanvasVirtWidth} Set/get canvas width
@ENDNODE

